 connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Briwere","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Pierre, Adrien, Aurele, Benedicte, Benoit, Colette, Fernand, Gaston, Marcel, Micheline.","French (<b>Brière</b>): topographic name from a regional variant of Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heather’ (see   Bruyere  ), or a habitational name from La Brière, the name of several places mainly in the northern part of France, from the same word.","History: Jean Brière from Clarbec in Calvados, France, married Jeanne Grandin in Quebec City, QC, in 1671."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruyere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Fernand, Jacques, Marcel.","French (<b>Bruyère</b>): from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heather’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived in a place where heather grew, or a habitational name from one of the places in France (for example in Calvados) named with this word. Compare   Labruyere  .","Altered form (<b>Bruyère</b>) of French <b>Bruguier</b>: habitational name from (Le) Bruguier, the name of several places in the southeastern part of France, a cognate of 1 above."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Briwere Barew was born in 1365, in West Horsley, Surrey, England as the daughter of John Barew. She married Sir James Berners in 1380, in West Horsley, Surrey, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1